Sharpless 249 and the Jellyfish Nebula Image Credit  Copyright  Cesar Blanco Gonzalez Explanation  Normally faint and elusive  the Jellyfish Nebula is caught in this alluring telescopic mosaic

The scene is anchored right and left by two bright stars  Mu and Eta Geminorum  at the foot of the celestial twin while the Jellyfish Nebula is the brighter arcing ridge of emission with dangling tentacles below and right of center
In fact  the cosmic jellyfish is part of bubbleshaped supernova remnant IC 443  the expanding debris cloud from a massive star that exploded
Light from the explosion first reached planet Earth over 30000 years ago
Like its cousin in astrophysical waters the Crab Nebula supernova remnant  the Jellyfish Nebula is known to harbor a neutron star  the remnant of the collapsed stellar core
An emission nebula cataloged as Sharpless 249 fills the field at the upper left
The Jellyfish Nebula is about 5000 lightyears away
At that distance  this narrowband composite image would be about 300 lightyears across
